  "text": "A crucial design consideration for SLP is to accommodate the received signal of each user k into a pre-specified region, called constructive interference (CI) region, corresponding to the intended symbol s k . The CI regions, which are modulationspecific regions, have been defined in several ways in the literature; see, e.g., [CITATION_1] , [CITATION_2] , [CITATION_3] . As mentioned earlier, we focus on the so-called distance-preserving CI regions [CITATION_4] , which are defined in a generic form that is applicable to any given (two-dimensional) modulation scheme.",
